      <hedline>
        <hl1>Houses of Worship</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Rev Richard G Grein letter responds to Oct 22 news article; applauds New York City Council's decision to award $1 million toward rehabilitation of landmark Eldridge Street Synagogue on Lower East Side (M)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The New York City Council's decision to award $1 million toward the rehabilitation of the landmark Eldridge Street Synagogue on the Lower East Side should be applauded (news article, Oct. 22).</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The New York City Council's decision to award $1 million toward the rehabilitation of the landmark Eldridge Street Synagogue on the Lower East Side should be applauded (news article, Oct. 22).</p>
        <p>Religious buildings are as much a part of the rich fabric of New York as are our skyscrapers, bridges, schools, museums, parks and train stations. The City Council's action recognizes not only the wide range of community services that religious buildings house, but also the buildings' importance as part of our cultural and historical patrimony.</p>
        <p>Let us hope that this initiative paves the way for a city program that does not categorically exclude architecturally and historically significant buildings simply because they are owned by religious organizations.</p>
        <p>(Rev.) RICHARD F. GREIN  New York, Oct. 24, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is bishop of the Diocese of New York of the Episcopal Church.</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
